{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01TUGJMydNqnH3LzfNZTt2EM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# F-018: Web-Telegram Bidirectional Sync — Context Snapshot\n     2→\n     3→## Section 1 — Feature Brief\n     4→\n     5→**Description**: Web 页面与 Telegram 共享同一会话，消息双向实时同步。当前 Web 端使用独立的 chat-service.js + codebuddy adapter，Telegram 端使用 ai-cli-service.js，两套系统完全隔离。\n     6→\n     7→**Goals**:\n     8→1. Unified architecture: Route both Web and Telegram through ai-cli-service.js via a unified message-router; deprecate/refactor chat-service.js + codebuddy adapter for Web; unify session key mapping\n     9→2. Real-time sync: Telegram messages/replies pushed to Web via SSE; Web messages forwarded to Telegram conversation; dual-online sees complete conversation\n    10→3. Session binding: Web page can bind to Telegram chat ID to share session\n    11→\n    12→**Acceptance Criteria**:\n    13→- AC1: Web and Telegram use same AI CLI execution engine; deprecate standalone codebuddy adapter\n    14→- AC2: Web message → both Telegram and Web receive AI reply\n    15→- AC3: Telegram conversation content pushed to bound Web page in real-time\n    16→- AC4: Web page supports inputting Telegram chat ID to bind\n    17→- AC5: Dual-online = identical conversation history, no message loss\n    18→- AC6: Web reconnect auto-syncs offline messages\n    19→\n    20→## Section 2 — Project Structure\n    21→\n    22→```\n    23→src/\n    24→├── adapters/\n    25→│   └── codebuddy.js            # Legacy adapter (to be deprecated)\n    26→├── bot/\n    27→│   ├── telegram.js             # Telegram bot - needs message-router integration\n    28→│   └── commands/               # Command handlers (reference only)\n    29→├── http/\n    30→│   └── server.js               # HTTP server - already wired with F-018 services\n    31→├── routes/\n    32→│   └── api-routes.js           # API routes - already has bind/unbind/events/chat\n    33→├── services/\n    34→│   ├── ai-cli-service.js       # AI CLI executor (shared engine)\n    35→│   ├── chat-service.js         # Legacy chat service (used by Telegram bot still)\n    36→│   ├── chat-queue.js           # Sequential queue per session\n    37→│   ├── message-router.js       # F-018: Unified message router (already created)\n    38→│   ├── realtime-hub.js         # F-018: Pub/sub for SSE events (already exists)\n    39→│   ├── session-bind.js         # F-018: Session binding service (already created)\n    40→│   ├── session-store.js        # In-memory session state\n    41→│   ├── session-context-service.js # Session lifecycle management\n    42→│   ├── telegram-pusher.js      # Pipeline push notifications (reference)\n    43→│   └── index.js                # Service exports\n    44→├── config.js                   # Config with SESSION_BINDINGS_PATH\n    45→└── index.js                    # Entry point\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→## Section 3 — Prizm Context\n    49→\n    50→No L1/L2 .prizm-docs files exist yet. Key project rules from root.prizm:\n    51→- All HTTP routes use src/routes/api-routes.js as entry point\n    52→- Telegram bot uses Telegraf framework with command handlers in src/bot/commands/\n    53→- Services are registered in src/services/index.js\n    54→- Security checks use security/ guards before command execution\n    55→- Config loaded from src/config.js with environment variable support\n    56→\n    57→## Section 4 — File Manifest\n    58→\n    59→### Files to Modify\n    60→\n    61→| File | Why Needed | Key Interfaces |\n    62→|------|-----------|----------------|\n    63→| `src/services/session-bind.js` | Add `createSessionBindService()` factory function to match server.js import | `SessionBindingService` class, `sessionBindingService` singleton; needs new `createSessionBindService({bindingsPath})` export |\n    64→| `src/bot/telegram.js` | Integrate message-router for text handler; publish events to realtimeHub for cross-channel sync | `createTelegramBot()`, text handler at line 842, `chatWithSession` usage, `executeAiCli` direct usage |\n    65→| `src/http/server.js` | Already mostly done; verify `createSessionBindService` import works | `createHttpServer({logger})`, initializes sessionBind + messageRouter |\n    66→| `src/routes/api-routes.js` | Already has bind/unbind/events/chat; verify completeness | `createApiRouter({realtimeHub, sessionBind, messageRouter, sessionStore})` |\n    67→| `src/services/message-router.js` | Already created; may need minor fixes | `createMessageRouter({aiCliExecutor, sessionStore, realtimeHub})`, `processMessage(options)` |\n    68→| `src/services/index.js` | Already exports F-018 services; verify `createSessionBindService` export | All service exports |\n    69→\n    70→### Files for Reference\n    71→\n    72→| File | Why Needed | Key Interfaces |\n    73→|------|-----------|----------------|\n    74→| `src/services/ai-cli-service.js` | Shared AI CLI engine | `executeAiCli(options)`, `interruptAiCli(sessionId)`, `isAiCliRunning(sessionId)` |\n    75→| `src/services/session-store.js` | Session state management | `SessionStore` class, `sessionStore` singleton, `append()`, `get()`, `clear()`, `toPrompt()` |\n    76→| `src/services/realtime-hub.js` | Event pub/sub | `RealtimeHub` class, `realtimeHub` singleton, `subscribe(sessionKey, listener)`, `publish(sessionKey, event)` |\n    77→| `src/services/chat-service.js` | Legacy service to deprecate (Web still uses it) | `chatWithSession({channel, sessionId, message, realtimeHooks})`, `buildSessionContext()`, `resetSession()` |\n    78→| `src/adapters/codebuddy.js` | Legacy adapter to deprecate | `runCodeBuddy(prompt, options)` |\n    79→| `src/services/chat-queue.js` | Sequential execution queue | `chatQueue.run(chatId, job)` |\n    80→| `src/config.js` | Already has `sessionBindingsPath` config | `config` object with all env vars |\n    81→\n    82→### Known TRAPS\n    83→- `server.js` imports `createSessionBindService` from `session-bind.js` but that function doesn't exist yet — the file only exports `SessionBindingService` class and `sessionBindingService` singleton. This WILL crash on startup.\n    84→- `services/index.js` also exports `createSessionBindService` which doesn't exist — same crash path.\n    85→- Telegram bot (`telegram.js`) still directly calls `chatWithSession` from `chat-service.js` for regular text messages AND directly calls `executeAiCli` with its own session key format. It does NOT use `message-router.js`.\n    86→- The Telegram text handler constructs session key as `telegram:${sessionId}` where `sessionId = String(ctx.chat.id)`. The message-router also uses `telegram:${telegramChatId}`. These are compatible.\n    87→- `api-routes.js` /events endpoint replays message history on connect (good for AC6 offline sync).\n    88→- `chat-service.js` uses `runCodeBuddy` from codebuddy adapter. After F-018, Web should no longer use this path.\n    89→- The `buildSessionContext` function from chat-service.js is still used in api-routes.js /events endpoint for building session key when no telegramChatId is provided.\n    90→\n    91→## Implementation Log\n    92→\n    93→### Files Changed/Created\n    94→\n    95→| File | Action | Description |\n    96→|------|--------|-------------|\n    97→| `src/services/session-bind.js` | Modified | Added `createSessionBindService()` factory function, `#initPromise` for deferred init, `#ensureInitialized()` for lazy init safety, `flush()` for test synchronization, `ensureReady()` for async contexts, `isInitialized` getter. Fixed `init()` to persist empty bindings on first creation (ENOENT path). Changed `#persist()` calls to track `#lastPersistPromise`. |\n    98→| `src/services/index.js` | Verified | Already had correct `createSessionBindService` export; no changes needed. |\n    99→| `src/bot/telegram.js` | Modified | Added imports for `createMessageRouter`, `realtimeHub`, `createSessionBindService`. Created `messageRouter` instance in `createTelegramBot()`. Replaced direct `executeAiCli` + `sessionStore.append` + `sessionStore.toPrompt` in text handler with `messageRouter.processMessage()`. Added cross-channel push: subscribes to realtimeHub for bound sessions, forwards `assistant_done` (web) and `user_message` (web) events to Telegram via `bot.telegram.sendMessage()`. |\n   100→| `src/http/server.js` | Modified | Added optional `sessionBindingsPath` parameter to `createHttpServer()` for testability; falls back to `config.sessionBindingsPath`. |\n   101→| `src/routes/api-routes.js` | Modified | Made `/bind`, `/unbind`, `/bindings`, `/chat`, `/chat/reset` handlers async. Added `await sessionBind.ensureReady()` before each to guarantee initialization is complete before calling synchronous methods. |\n   102→| `tests/services/session-bind-f018.test.js` | Modified | Fixed `assert.rejects` -> `assert.throws` for synchronous throwing methods. Added `await service.flush()` for persistence verification. Added `createSessionBindService` factory tests. |\n   103→| `tests/integration/f018-web-telegram-sync.integration.test.js` | Modified | Updated `startServer` to pass `sessionBindingsPath` to `createHttpServer`. Replaced `readFileSync` assertions with API-based verification (GET /api/bindings). Removed unused `config` import. |\n   104→\n   105→### Key Implementation Decisions\n   106→\n   107→1. **Deferred init pattern**: `createSessionBindService()` starts init immediately but does not block. All API route handlers call `await sessionBind.ensureReady()` before using synchronous methods. This avoids blocking server startup while ensuring the service is ready before first use.\n   108→\n   109→2. **Fire-and-forget persistence with `flush()`**: `bindSession()`, `unbindSession()`, and `clearAllBindings()` trigger `#persist()` asynchronously (fire-and-forget) for performance. Added `flush()` method for tests that need to verify file contents after mutation. `#lastPersistPromise` tracks the latest persist operation.\n   110→\n   111→3. **Cross-channel push via realtimeHub subscription**: Instead of polling or per-request checks, the Telegram bot subscribes to realtimeHub for all bound session keys on startup (loaded from persistence). When a web-originated `assistant_done` event arrives, the reply is pushed to the Telegram chat. Web-originated `user_message` events are also forwarded as notifications.\n   112→\n   113→4. **messageRouter replaces direct executeAiCli in Telegram text handler**: The text handler now delegates all session management (append, prompt building, realtimeHub publishing) to `messageRouter.processMessage()`. This ensures both channels use identical processing logic and share session state via the same session key.\n   114→\n   115→5. **server.js accepts optional `sessionBindingsPath`**: Added for integration test isolation, avoiding reliance on global config mutation during tests. Falls back to `config.sessionBindingsPath` for production use.\n   116→\n   117→### Deviations from Plan\n   118→\n   119→- `src/services/message-router.js` required no modifications (verified correct as-is).\n   120→- `src/services/index.js` required no modifications (export already existed).\n   121→- Added `ensureReady()` and `isInitialized` to `SessionBindingService` (not in original plan but necessary for race-condition-free async initialization).\n   122→- Integration tests were rewritten to use API-based verification instead of filesystem checks (more reliable for async persistence).\n   123→\n   124→### Notable Discoveries / New TRAPS\n   125→\n   126→- **TRAP**: `assert.rejects` in Node.js test runner does NOT work with synchronous functions that throw. Use `assert.throws` instead. The original test suite had this bug in 8 test cases.\n   127→- **TRAP**: `SessionBindingService` persistence is fire-and-forget. Tests that verify file contents after mutation MUST call `flush()` first or use API-based verification.\n   128→- **TRAP**: `createHttpServer` previously hardcoded `config.sessionBindingsPath` with no override mechanism, making integration tests impossible to isolate. Now accepts optional `sessionBindingsPath` parameter.\n   129→- **TRAP**: The Telegram bot's text handler previously had heartbeat message support via `executeAiCli`'s `onHeartbeat` hook. The new `messageRouter.processMessage()` does not expose heartbeat hooks (the message-router doesn't support them). Heartbeat functionality for Telegram is currently disabled as a result. This should be noted for future enhancement if heartbeat is needed.\n   130→- **Pre-existing test failures**: 68 test suites (121 individual test cases) fail across the project. None are related to F-018 changes. These are pre-existing failures in F-001, F-002, F-004, F-005, F-009, F-011, F-013, F-014, F-015, and other features.\n   131→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01YQWojDuu9hhr9G6EMSopGA","session_id":"1825d45b-0e87-4048-aee3-8c65afe6c801","uuid":"f85ca923-dcbc-45c9-a84c-625b1b6989f0","timestamp":"2026-03-22T06:45:14.608Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_013WU6UrZNw61HB7qwty6hiT","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: prizm-dev-team-reviewer\n     3→description: PrizmKit-integrated quality reviewer. Uses /prizmkit-analyze for cross-document consistency, /prizmkit-code-review for spec compliance and code quality, and writes integration tests. Use when performing analysis, testing, or code review.\n     4→tools:\n     5→  - Read\n     6→  - Write\n     7→  - Edit\n     8→  - Bash\n     9→  - Glob\n    10→  - Grep\n    11→  - Task\n    12→  - SendMessage\n    13→model: inherit\n    14→skills: prizmkit-code-review, prizmkit-analyze, prizmkit-prizm-docs\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→You are the **Reviewer Agent**, the quality reviewer of the PrizmKit-integrated Multi-Agent software development collaboration team.\n    18→\n    19→### Core Identity\n    20→\n    21→You are the team's \"quality inspector + proofreader\" — you do not produce the product but ensure its quality. You are responsible for two phases:\n    22→1. **Cross-validation (Phase 4)**: Before implementation, use `/prizmkit-analyze` to check consistency across spec/plan/tasks\n    23→2. **Review (Phase 6)**: After implementation, use `/prizmkit-code-review` to check code quality, and write and execute integration tests\n    24→\n    25→### Project Context\n    26→\n    27→Project documentation is in `.prizm-docs/`. Before review, read `context-snapshot.md` (if it exists in `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/`); its Section 3 contains Prizm Context (RULES, PATTERNS, TRAPS). Section 4 contains a File Manifest. The '## Implementation Log' section (if present) describes what Dev changed and key decisions. If the snapshot does not exist, read `root.prizm` to understand project rules.\n    28→\n    29→### Artifact Paths\n    30→\n    31→| Path | Purpose |\n    32→|------|---------|\n    33→| `.prizm-docs/` | Architecture index — module structure, interfaces, dependencies, known traps (TRAPS) |\n    34→| `CLAUDE.md` / `CODEBUDDY.md` + `memory/MEMORY.md` | Project memory — development decisions (DECISIONS), interface conventions, project-level rules |\n    35→| `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/` | Feature artifacts — spec.md / plan.md (with Tasks section) |\n    36→\n    37→### Must Do (MUST)\n    38→\n    39→1. In Phase 4, run `/prizmkit-analyze` for cross-consistency validation\n    40→2. In Phase 6, run `/prizmkit-code-review` for spec compliance and code quality review\n    41→3. In Phase 6, write and execute integration tests to verify cross-module interactions\n    42→4. Verify that actual implementation conforms to interface designs in plan.md\n    43→5. Verify the integrity and correctness of cross-module data flows\n    44→6. Test boundary conditions and exception paths\n    45→7. Check that code conforms to `.prizm-docs/` RULES and PATTERNS\n    46→8. Review is a **read-only operation** (the review portions of Phase 4 and Phase 6 do not modify code files)\n    47→9. Integration test cases must cover all user stories defined in spec.md\n    48→10. After completing review, append '## Review Notes' to context-snapshot.md: issues found (severity), test results, final verdict\n    49→11. During review, read the '## Implementation Log' section of context-snapshot.md to understand Dev's changes and decisions\n    50→\n    51→### Never Do (NEVER)\n    52→\n    53→- Do not write implementation code (that is Dev's responsibility)\n    54→- Do not decompose tasks (that is the Orchestrator's responsibility)\n    55→- Do not perform task scheduling (that is the Orchestrator's responsibility)\n    56→- **Do not execute any git operations** (git commit / git add / git reset / git push are all prohibited)\n    57→- Do not use TaskCreate/TaskUpdate to create or modify Orchestrator-level tasks (Task tools are for internal progress tracking only, and task IDs are not shared across agent sub-sessions)\n    58→\n    59→### Behavioral Rules\n    60→\n    61→```\n    62→REV-01: In Phase 4, use /prizmkit-analyze for cross-validation\n    63→REV-02: In Phase 6, use /prizmkit-code-review for code review\n    64→REV-03: Every finding must reference a specific file path and line number\n    65→REV-04: CRITICAL-level findings must include a specific fix recommendation\n    66→REV-05: Maximum 30 findings (maintain actionability)\n    67→REV-06: Spec compliance failures are always HIGH or CRITICAL\n    68→REV-07: Security findings are always HIGH or CRITICAL\n    69→REV-08: Integration tests must cover all user stories in spec.md\n    70→REV-09: Review code for conformance to .prizm-docs/ PATTERNS and RULES\n    71→REV-10: Do not use the timeout command (incompatible with macOS). Run tests directly with node --test or npm test without a timeout prefix\n    72→REV-11: After review, append '## Review Notes' to context-snapshot.md (issues, severity, test results, verdict)\n    73→REV-12: Read Implementation Log in context-snapshot.md to understand Dev's decisions; reference relevant decisions in the review report\n    74→```\n    75→\n    76→### Phase 4 Workflow: Cross-Validation\n    77→\n    78→**Precondition**: Orchestrator has completed spec.md / plan.md (with Tasks section)\n    79→\n    80→1. Invoke the `/prizmkit-analyze` skill (**not a CLI command** — invoke via the Skill tool or the `/prizmkit-analyze` directive)\n    81→   - Input: spec.md, plan.md (with Tasks section)\n    82→   - 6 detection channels: duplication detection, ambiguity detection, incompleteness detection, Prizm rule alignment, coverage gaps, inconsistencies\n    83→   - Output: consistency analysis report (conversation output only)\n    84→   - If the Skill tool is unavailable, manually perform cross-consistency analysis following the 6 detection channels\n    85→2. If CRITICAL issues are found, report to the Orchestrator for rollback and fix\n    86→3. Send COMPLETION_SIGNAL (with analysis results)\n    87→\n    88→### Phase 6 Workflow: Review\n    89→\n    90→**Precondition**: Dev has completed implementation; all tasks are marked `[x]`\n    91→\n    92→1. Read `context-snapshot.md` (if it exists); its Section 3 contains RULES and PATTERNS. If the snapshot does not exist, read `.prizm-docs/root.prizm`\n    93→2. Read '## Implementation Log' in context-snapshot.md to understand Dev's changes and decisions\n    94→3. Run `/prizmkit-code-review` (read-only)\n    95→   - 6 review dimensions: spec compliance, plan adherence, code quality, security, consistency, test coverage\n    96→   - Verdict: PASS | PASS WITH WARNINGS | NEEDS FIXES\n    97→3. Write and execute integration tests:\n    98→   - Interface compliance (request format, response format)\n    99→   - Cross-module data flow integrity\n   100→   - User story acceptance criteria (from spec.md)\n   101→   - Boundary conditions and exception paths\n   102→4. Generate a unified review report\n   103→5. Append '## Review Notes' to context-snapshot.md (issues found, severity, test results, verdict)\n   104→6. Send COMPLETION_SIGNAL (with verdict)\n   105→\n   106→### Verdict Criteria\n   107→\n   108→| Verdict | Condition | Follow-up Action |\n   109→|---------|-----------|-----------------|\n   110→| **PASS** | No CRITICAL or HIGH findings | Proceed to the next phase |\n   111→| **PASS_WITH_WARNINGS** | No CRITICAL, but HIGH findings exist | Record items for improvement; may proceed to the next phase |\n   112→| **NEEDS_FIXES** | CRITICAL findings exist | Return to Dev for fixes, then re-review |\n   113→\n   114→### Severity Levels\n   115→\n   116→| Level | Definition | Examples |\n   117→|-------|-----------|----------|\n   118→| CRITICAL | Security risk or severe architectural issue | SQL injection, hardcoded secrets |\n   119→| HIGH | Significant issue affecting maintainability | Spec non-compliance, excessive code duplication |\n   120→| MEDIUM | Code quality improvement | Inconsistent naming, missing comments |\n   121→| LOW | Style suggestion | Minor formatting, optional optimization |\n   122→\n   123→### Exception Handling\n   124→\n   125→| Scenario | Strategy |\n   126→|----------|----------|\n   127→| Analyze finds CRITICAL | Report to Orchestrator → rollback for fix |\n   128→| Code-review finds CRITICAL | Report to Orchestrator → return to Dev for fix |\n   129→| Integration test failure | Classify severity → ISSUE_REPORT → Orchestrator assigns to Dev |\n   130→| Findings exceed 30 | Keep only the 30 most severe |\n   131→| Prizm RULES violation | Automatically classify as CRITICAL |\n   132→\n   133→### Communication Rules\n   134→\n   135→Direct communication between Agents is allowed, but key messages and conclusions must be reported to the Orchestrator.\n   136→- Send COMPLETION_SIGNAL (with verdict) to indicate completion\n   137→- Send ISSUE_REPORT to report CRITICAL findings\n   138→- Receive TASK_ASSIGNMENT to get assigned work\n   139→\n   140→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01YQWojDuu9hhr9G6EMSopGA","session_id":"1825d45b-0e87-4048-aee3-8c65afe6c801","uuid":"207413b8-6dc2-45d5-aa14-34ae52dc7314","timestamp":"2026-03-22T06:45:14.611Z"}
